<subSubSection id="C355653BFF84FF83FF64995C580AFC0C" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="79" pageId="21" pageNumber="78" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BF036B0FF84FF80FF64995C5EBEF83A" blockId="21.[151,1436,1802,2045]" pageId="21" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF84FF80FF64995C5B36F8E3" bold="true" box="[151,260,1802,1828]" pageId="21" pageNumber="78">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF84FF80FEE1995C5807F8E3" authorityName="Lieftinck" authorityYear="1935" box="[274,565,1802,1828]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="21" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phalantus">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF84FF80FEE1995C5807F8E3" box="[274,565,1802,1828]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="78">Macrogomphus phalantus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described, in detail, on the basis of two males and a female from W. Borneo, Singkawang, swamped forest near “Bakoean” (Bakuan, 
<collectingRegion id="498BF852FF84FF80FCB599785E4AF88F" box="[838,1144,1838,1865]" country="Indonesia" name="Kalimantan Barat" pageId="21" pageNumber="78">Kalimantan Barat Province</collectingRegion>
of 
<collectingCountry id="F3587620FF84FF80FB6E99785F3CF88E" box="[1181,1294,1838,1865]" name="Indonesia" pageId="21" pageNumber="78">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
), as “closely resembling 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF84FF80FEEE9905588FF8AB" authority="Selys" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1878" box="[285,701,1874,1900]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="21" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="parallelogramma" subSpecies="albardae">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF84FF80FEEE99055844F8AB" box="[285,630,1874,1900]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="78">M. parallelogramma albardae</emphasis>
Selys
</taxonomicName>
but much smaller and with differently shaped anal appendages’ (
<bibRefCitation id="EFDE4B41FF84FF80FF6D99205BB0F857" author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[158,386,1909,1936]" pageId="21" pageNumber="78" pagination="175 - 207" refId="ref18933" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1935) New and little known Odonata of the Oriental and Australian Regions. Treubia, 15 (2), 175 - 207." type="journal article" year="1935">Lieftinck 1935: 201</bibRefCitation>
). In the diagnosis, such details as “shorter discoidal triangle of the front wing, ... narrower and almost parallel-sided yellow bands on each side of the thorax, and ... more widely separated and more obliquely placed antehumeral thoracic stripes” were mentioned (
<bibRefCitation id="EFDE4B41FF84FF80FCF399E859D5F81F" author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[768,999,1981,2008]" pageId="21" pageNumber="78" pagination="175 - 207" refId="ref18933" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1935) New and little known Odonata of the Oriental and Australian Regions. Treubia, 15 (2), 175 - 207." type="journal article" year="1935">Lieftinck 1935: 203</bibRefCitation>
). The female was stated to differ from other species by a bifid median prominence on the occipital plate (which was not figured).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF036B0FF87FF83FF349ECF5F49FD87" blockId="22.[151,1437,153,971]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">
Lieftinck abstained from verbal description and comparison of the male anal appendages of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF87FF83FB2F9ECC5F42FF74" authorityName="Lieftinck" authorityYear="1935" box="[1244,1392,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phalantus">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF87FF83FB2F9ECC5F42FF74" box="[1244,1392,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. phalantus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but made a confusing statement: “The shape of the inner branch of the sup. anal apps. of the male rather suggests 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF87FF83FA8D9EE85BB1FF3C" authority="Fraser" authorityName="Fraser" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="borikhanensis">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF87FF83FA8D9EE85B06FF3C" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. borikhanensis</emphasis>
Fraser
</taxonomicName>
, from the 
<collectingCountry id="F3587620FF87FF83FE019EB7581AFF3C" box="[498,552,225,251]" name="Laos" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Laos</collectingCountry>
country...” (
<bibRefCitation id="EFDE4B41FF87FF83FD429EB759A6FF3C" author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[689,916,224,251]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" pagination="175 - 207" refId="ref18933" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1935) New and little known Odonata of the Oriental and Australian Regions. Treubia, 15 (2), 175 - 207." type="journal article" year="1935">Lieftinck 1935: 203</bibRefCitation>
). The (incorrect) drawing of the appendages of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF87FF83FF649F505B68FED8" authorityName="Fraser" authorityYear="1933" box="[151,346,261,287]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="borikhanensis">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF87FF83FF649F505B68FED8" box="[151,346,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. borikhanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDE4B41FF87FF83FE779F535824FED8" author="Fraser, F. C." box="[388,534,261,287]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" pagination="109 - 141" refId="ref18133" refString="Fraser, F. C. (1933) Dragonflies of the Laos country. Journal of Siam Society, Natural History Supplement, 9, 109 - 141." type="journal article" year="1933">Fraser (1933</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 6a, c; see 
<figureCitation id="13742A35FF87FF83FD4F9F53593EFED8" box="[700,780,261,287]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1818,1843]" captionTargetBox="[361,1227,186,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[350,1237,166,1806]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Anal appendages (a–h) and secondary genitalia (j–k) of Macrogomphus albardae as illustrated in literature: aafter Lieftinck (1935: fig. 9) (as M. parallelogramma albardae); b—after Orr (2005: p. 64) (as M. parallelogramma albardae); c—after Fraser (1933: fig. 8a, c) (as M. borikhanensis); d—after Asahina (1986: fig. 8–9) (as? M. phalantus): e, j—after Asahina (1986: fig. 4–6) (as M. borikhanensis); f, i—after Chao (1982: fig. 1, 3, 6) (as M. guilinensis); g—after Wilson (2005: fig. 17 d, e) (as M. guilinensis); h—after Karube (2014: fig. 13) (as M. guilinensis). Not to scale; j mirrored. Asterisk indicates the proximal inner swelling of the cercus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3995329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3995329/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Fig. 3c</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13742A35FF87FF83FCEB9F535906FED8" box="[792,820,261,287]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1914,1939]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,181,1894]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 8. Holotype of Macrogomphus borikhanensis Fraser, 1933 and its labels (BMNH): a—dorsal view; b—lateral view. Not to scale. Courtesy of Benjamin Price." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3995339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3995339/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">8d</figureCitation>
here) hardly resembles their structure in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF87FF83FAF29F505FA7FED8" authorityName="Lieftinck" authorityYear="1935" box="[1281,1429,261,287]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phalantus">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF87FF83FAF29F505FA7FED8" box="[1281,1429,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. phalantus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In fact, 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF87FF83FF039F7C5BB7FE84" authorityName="Lieftinck" authorityYear="1935" box="[240,389,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phalantus">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF87FF83FF039F7C5BB7FE84" box="[240,389,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. phalantus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
exhibits an unique distinct diagnostic character: in dorsal view, the proximal inner swelling of the cercus is very sharp and prominent, and shifted distally off the cercus cleft into its two branches, as indicated with an asterisk in 
<figureCitation id="13742A35FF87FF83FE9D9F275BF9FE4C" box="[366,459,368,395]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1898,1923]" captionTargetBox="[227,1361,166,1861]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[227,1361,166,1886]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 15. Details of male specimens of Macrogomphus phalantus: a–f—M. p. jayavarman subsp; nov., the holotype; gh—M. p. phalantus (After Lieftinck 1935: figs.11–12); a—head, frontal view; b–c,g—secondary genitalia, lateral view; d—anal appendages, dorsal view; e—ditto, lateral view; f—ditto, ventral view; h—dorsal and lateral view. Scale bar 1 mm. Asterisk indicates the proximal inner swellings of the cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3995353" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3995353/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Fig. 15h</figureCitation>
(after 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDE4B41FF87FF83FDEB9F2758F0FE4C" author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[536,706,368,395]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" pagination="175 - 207" refId="ref18933" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1935) New and little known Odonata of the Oriental and Australian Regions. Treubia, 15 (2), 175 - 207." type="journal article" year="1935">Lieftinck 1935</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 12). As a consequence, two more distal swellings are ‘compressed’ to locate closely to each other (
<figureCitation id="13742A35FF87FF83FDAC9FC358F0FE68" box="[607,706,404,431]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1898,1923]" captionTargetBox="[227,1361,166,1861]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[227,1361,166,1886]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 15. Details of male specimens of Macrogomphus phalantus: a–f—M. p. jayavarman subsp; nov., the holotype; gh—M. p. phalantus (After Lieftinck 1935: figs.11–12); a—head, frontal view; b–c,g—secondary genitalia, lateral view; d—anal appendages, dorsal view; e—ditto, lateral view; f—ditto, ventral view; h—dorsal and lateral view. Scale bar 1 mm. Asterisk indicates the proximal inner swellings of the cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3995353" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3995353/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Fig. 15h</figureCitation>
). In all illustrations and specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF87FF83FB869FC05ECDFE68" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1858" box="[1141,1279,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albardae">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF87FF83FB869FC05ECDFE68" box="[1141,1279,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. albardae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known to the author (
<figureCitation id="13742A35FF87FF83FF1D9FEF5B78FE14" box="[238,330,441,467]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1868,1893]" captionTargetBox="[187,1400,166,1856]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[187,1400,166,1856]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Details of some male specimens of Macrogomphus albardae kept in RMNH (courtesy of Jan van Tol): a–d—the male syntype (the labels ‘Holotype’ are misleading); e—“W. Borneo, 0 m. / Singkawang / Penanring / L. Coomans de Ruiter / 24. II. 1932”; f—“S. Sumatra / Terbanggi-Hilir / nr. Menggala / Lampang distr. / 18. VIII. 1936 / M. Bartels”; a—general habitus; b, e–f—S10 and anal appendages, dorsal view; c—head and thorax, dorsolateral view; d—labels of the male syntype. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3995327" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3995327/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Figs. 2b</figureCitation>
,e–f, 3a–h, 4c, 7a,c, 9a, 11), the proximal inner swelling (indicated by an asterisk in 
<figureCitation id="13742A35FF87FF83FB049FEF5F72FE14" box="[1271,1344,441,467]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1815,1840]" captionTargetBox="[413,1211,196,1803]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[376,1211,174,1803]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. Details of the specimens identified as Macrogomphus parallelogramma s. str.: the holotype female (a) and males (b–i), as illustrated by Hagen in Selys (1858: planche 5, fig. 5 and planche 20, fig. 4) (a–f); of a male specimen from “Java mer.” from RBINS collection (Courtesy of Jérôme Constant) (g–j): and of a male specimen from “W. Java. 100 m. /, Djaniga / Tjibarangbang / 30.IV.1939 / over stream p.m. / M.A. Lieftinck” and kept in RMNH (courtesy of Jan van Tol) (k,l); a—head, dorsal view; b,h—S8–10 (dorsal view); c,i—ditto (lateral view); d—S10 and appendages, lateral view; e—epiproct, ventral view; f–g,k—cerci, posteriodorsal view; j–k—labels.Asterisk marks the bulge of the inner cercus margin. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3995325" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3995325/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Fig. 1l</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation id="13742A35FF87FF83FA849FEF5FA6FE13" box="[1399,1428,441,468]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1818,1843]" captionTargetBox="[361,1227,186,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[350,1237,166,1806]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Anal appendages (a–h) and secondary genitalia (j–k) of Macrogomphus albardae as illustrated in literature: aafter Lieftinck (1935: fig. 9) (as M. parallelogramma albardae); b—after Orr (2005: p. 64) (as M. parallelogramma albardae); c—after Fraser (1933: fig. 8a, c) (as M. borikhanensis); d—after Asahina (1986: fig. 8–9) (as? M. phalantus): e, j—after Asahina (1986: fig. 4–6) (as M. borikhanensis); f, i—after Chao (1982: fig. 1, 3, 6) (as M. guilinensis); g—after Wilson (2005: fig. 17 d, e) (as M. guilinensis); h—after Karube (2014: fig. 13) (as M. guilinensis). Not to scale; j mirrored. Asterisk indicates the proximal inner swelling of the cercus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3995329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3995329/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">3b</figureCitation>
) is smoother and invariably located at the level of the cleft, more proximal swellings also being smoother. The importance of this character could be disputable if I had not collect a series of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF87FF83FC189C575EA8FDDC" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1858" box="[1003,1178,513,539]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF87FF83FC189C575EA8FDDC" box="[1003,1178,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Macrogomphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males with exactly the same cerci as far from the presumed range of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF87FF83FD649C705919FDF8" authorityName="Lieftinck" authorityYear="1935" box="[663,811,549,575]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phalantus">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF87FF83FD649C705919FDF8" box="[663,811,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. phalantus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as in 
<collectingCountry id="F3587620FF87FF83FC9E9C7359D1FDF8" box="[877,995,549,575]" name="Cambodia" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Cambodia</collectingCountry>
, but in a similar habitat (see below).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF036B0FF87FF83FF349C1F5E63FD34" blockId="22.[151,1437,153,971]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">
Later the species was reported for Palembang in eastern 
<collectingRegion id="498BF852FF87FF83FCAA9C1F5984FDA4" box="[857,950,585,611]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Utara" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Sumatra</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFDE4B41FF87FF83FC3B9C1F5E45FDA4" author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[968,1143,584,611]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" pagination="1 - 202" refId="ref18965" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1954) Handlist of Malaysian Odonata. A catalogue of the dragonflies of the Malay Peninsula, Sumatra, Java and Borneo, including the adjacent small islands. Treubia, 22 (Supplement), 1 - 202." type="journal article" year="1954">Lieftinck 1954</bibRefCitation>
). All so scanty reports of this species refer to a habitat unusual for gomphids: swamped forest in low country (
<bibRefCitation id="EFDE4B41FF87FF83FBBE9C3B5ECAFD40" author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[1101,1272,620,647]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" pagination="175 - 207" refId="ref18933" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1935) New and little known Odonata of the Oriental and Australian Regions. Treubia, 15 (2), 175 - 207." type="journal article" year="1935">Lieftinck 1935</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDE4B41FF87FF83FAF79C3A5F0DFD40" author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[1284,1343,620,647]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" pagination="67 - 87" refId="ref19012" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1955) Synopsis of the dragonflies (Odonata) of Ceylon. Zoologische Mededelingen, 34 (5), 67 - 87." type="journal article" year="1955">1955</bibRefCitation>
), a river upstream the 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF87FF83FEDD9CC45B5BFD6C" box="[302,361,658,683]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Nypa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF87FF83FEDD9CC45B5BFD6C" box="[302,361,658,683]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Nypa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
stand and mangroves in lowland rainforest (Dow 2016). The ‘snorkel’ of the elongated terminal abdominal segments of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF87FF83FE229CE358B2FD08" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1858" box="[465,640,693,719]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF87FF83FE229CE358B2FD08" box="[465,640,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Macrogomphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
larvae suggest ability to live in silt low of oxygen, nevertheless other 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF87FF83FF649C8F5B74FD34" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1858" box="[151,326,729,755]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF87FF83FF649C8F5B74FD34" box="[151,326,729,755]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Macrogomphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. are usually found near running water at foothills and mountains.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF036B0FF87FF83FF349CAB580AFC0C" blockId="22.[151,1437,153,971]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">
While studying 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF87FF83FE8F9CAB5BE9FCD0" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1793" box="[380,475,765,791]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Odonata</taxonomicName>
of the great Lake Tonlé Sap in 
<collectingCountry id="F3587620FF87FF83FCB09CAB5984FCD0" box="[835,950,765,791]" name="Cambodia" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Cambodia</collectingCountry>
I was struck to find numerous 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF87FF83FAEA9CA85AFEFCFC" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1858" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF87FF83FAEA9CA85AFEFCFC" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Macrogomphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. at a temporarily inundated forest margin on its northern bank (at the low water season). The male anal appendages appeared to correspond to 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF87FF83FDBF9D1058EDFC98" authorityName="Lieftinck" authorityYear="1935" box="[588,735,837,863]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phalantus">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF87FF83FDBF9D1058EDFC98" box="[588,735,837,863]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. phalantus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the unusual habitat was exactly as in that species. Certain differences of the collected specimens from the original description by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDE4B41FF87FF83FC5B9D3F5E53FC44" author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[936,1121,872,899]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" pagination="175 - 207" refId="ref18933" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1935) New and little known Odonata of the Oriental and Australian Regions. Treubia, 15 (2), 175 - 207." type="journal article" year="1935">Lieftinck (1935)</bibRefCitation>
, as well as the huge distance of the newly found population from the presumed range of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D33FF87FF83FCC69DD8598DFC60" box="[821,959,909,935]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phalantu">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA2FF87FF83FCC69DD8598DFC60" box="[821,959,909,935]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. phalantu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s in Borneo and Sumatra, suggested a new subspecies which is described below.
</paragraph>
